    "question_id" : 75593543,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>A 204 (No Content) response should not include a body; &quot;No Content&quot; means <em>no content</em>. 204 is pretty standard for a DELETE response (when it succeeds of course), but I also see 200 OK.</p>\n<p>For PUT requests that succeed, it's typical to return a 200 response status with the updated resource (entity, etc) as the body. That saves clients from making another round-trip GET to the server to get the updated resource.</p>\n<p>By the way, Spring provides an annotation to specify the response status code so you don't have to be so verbose in the code. For example:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>@DeleteMapping(&quot;/categories/{id}&quot;)\n@ResponseStatus(value = HttpStatus.NO_CONTENT)\npublic void deleteById(@PathVariable long id) {\n    categoryService.deleteById(id);\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 320962,
        "reputation" : 33566,
        "user_id" : 639520,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 72,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/KzMc4.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "E-Riz",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/639520/e-riz"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1677596298,
      "post_id" : 75593693,
      "comment_id" : 133366765,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "A 201 (Created) response would be incorrect or at least misleading for a PUT, which should be for <i>updates</i> to an existing resource, not creating new resources."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 444292,
        "reputation" : 1,
