    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9763630,
      "reputation" : 19551,
      "user_id" : 7237884,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/0IOoaSCY.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Panagiotis Bougioukos",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7237884/panagiotis-bougioukos"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1677659539,
    "last_edit_date" : 1677659539,
    "creation_date" : 1677596733,
    "answer_id" : 75593791,
    "question_id" : 75593543,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>As described in <a href=\"https://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec9.html#sec9.6\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Http Protocol RFC 2616</a></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>9.6 PUT</strong></p>\n<p>If an existing resource is modified, either the 200 (OK) or 204 (No\nContent) response codes SHOULD be sent to indicate successful\ncompletion of the request.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Also</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>9.7 DELETE</strong></p>\n<p>A successful response SHOULD be 200 (OK) if the response includes an entity describing the status, 202 (Accepted) if the action\nhas not yet been enacted, or 204 (No Content) if the action has been\nenacted but the response does not include an entity.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Edit</strong>: To clarify. The part in delete operation that describes the status 200 (OK) expects an entity not of the actual business deleted or not in database, but another object entity which is able to describe the status of the delete action (DONE, PENDING, FAILED...).</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 44319639,
      "reputation" : 32,
      "user_id" : 31692030,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6e0828ef5d5b73747b3ad3e528290382?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Sathya Priya",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/31692030/sathya-priya"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1760532569,
    "creation_date" : 1760532569,
    "answer_id" : 79791185,
    "question_id" : 75593543,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can use below format for standard PUT and DELETE End points:</p>\n<p>Assuming you have Employee table and you are updating employee details as part of PUT request and delete employee entry as part of DELETE request.</p>\n<pre><code>\n@PutMapping(&quot;/employees/{empId}&quot;)\npublic ResponseEntity&lt;Employee&gt; updateEmployeeData(@PathVariable Long empId, @RequestBody Employee emp){\n    Employee empUpdated= employeeService.updateEmp(empId,emp);\n    return ResponseEntity.ok(empUpdated);\n    //this will share HttpStatusCode 200 along with updated employee details\n}\n\n@DeleteMapping(&quot;/eomployees/{empid}&quot;)\npublic ResponseEntity&lt;Void&gt; removeEmployee(@PathVariable Long empId){\n    employeeService.removeEmp(empId);\n    return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();\n    //this will return HttpStatusCode 204 with no content\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
